english:
  title: A Letter in Response to Master Cam Gong of Dongfeng Mountain
  author: Nam Hyo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Not long ago, I received your boundless kindness when you saw me off at Lushan, crossing the distant Tiger Creek—a grace and honor beyond measure. Moreover, though I am but shallow and commonplace, lacking even the sorrow of aspiration or the wisdom to draw conclusions from a corner, you have taught me the way to conduct myself and order my affairs. Drawing upon the examples of the ancients, you explained and reexplained with patient care. My gratitude knows no bounds, yet I fear my very bones must crumble into dust before I could ever repay such kindness.

    Yet I have long heard this said: though a thousand pounds is the heaviest weight, a strong man lifts it with ease; though a single feather is the lightest thing, a fly cannot bear it—for such is the nature of strength and weakness. So too with human conduct. Some walk the middle way with effortless grace, while others must strain and toil to follow the path. Those who struggle do not wish to advance without thought or to find the way without effort, but their murky nature and turbid constitution are theirs from birth itself. Therefore they must labor a hundredfold, ever pressing forward without rest—for such is the thickness or thinness of one's virtue.

    The virtue of wine is detailed in the Five Classics and the histories. When used rightly, it brings host and guest into harmony, nourishes the aged, graces the feast with refinement, reaches heaven and earth without fault. When sorrow meets wine, it dissolves; when melancholy meets wine, it opens wide. The heart grows joyful, at one with heaven and earth, joined with the transformation of ten thousand things. In the company of ancient sages, a hundred years pass like leisure. But when wine is misused—when one goes about with tangled hair, singing wildly and dancing in frenzy, shouting in the midst of ceremony, stumbling through courtesies—then propriety crumbles, righteousness perishes, and chaos erupts without restraint. Some lose their very bodies, some their families, and some have even lost kingdoms. Such is the calamity of wine. Yet when the Duke of Zhou and Confucius drank, they were not thrown into disorder. Such is the virtue of wine, yet when Chen Zun and Zhou Yi drank, they brought ruin upon themselves. The difference between gain and loss is thinner than a hair—how could one not be careful?

    Thus the common person, lacking firm resolve and drinking without restraint, finds sweet flavors leading them astray. The more they drink, the more disordered they become, until they descend into drunken excess without knowing how. This is the inevitable logic of things. The scholar whose will is weak must cultivate vigilance within, cut off the roots of chaos, and practice discipline a hundredfold more than others. Only then can he escape this calamity.

    This is why the Scriptures record the warnings against wine, and the Poetry contains verses on restraint at the feast. Yang Xiong composed admonitions on this matter, and Fan Lu wrote poems. How could I not wish to hold a cup with ease, advancing and withdrawing with proper courtesy at village feasts and archery contests? But I fear my heart is weak and my virtue thin—that the sweet taste would overcome me, and lacking restraint, I would fall into madness I could not master, like a fly unable to bear even a single feather.

    Since my youth, I have been drawn to fermented grains. In middle age, my tongue and teeth suffered no small trouble, and I descended into wine-fueled excess. I resigned myself to permanent abstinence, my body become a slave to material things, my spirit a servant to flesh. My essence has wasted away from those former days, and my virtue has daily betrayed my original resolve, descending into such disgrace that I have brought drunken shame upon my own household. This is unfilial! Mencius has said that one who loves games and wine and neglects the sustenance of parents commits the great wrong of unfilial conduct. How much more so with drunken excess? When I awake to myself, I find myself first among the three thousand sins. How could I ever raise a cup again?

    Therefore I have sworn an oath to heaven and earth, consulted the six spirits, pledged my heart, and informed my mother: from this day forward, I shall not drink unless commanded by my lord or father. I do this because I despise the state of drunkenness. As for drinking the blessing after sacrifice, or the ceremonial cup at a feast, or the fine wine that wets the mouth without bringing disorder—from these I would not shrink. Such is the general course of my resolve.

    Even should you offer me further teachings on wine, I cannot break the oath I have sworn—for my words reflect my heart, and my heart cannot deceive itself. If my heart could be deceived, how could I deceive the spirits? If I could deceive the spirits, how could I dismiss heaven and earth? If I could dismiss heaven and earth, where would my body find rest? Moreover, my mother who raised me has always cautioned me to drink sparingly. When she heard of my vow, her face lit with joy. How could I break such a promise?

    Alas, Qu Yuan wakeful and Liu Ling in his cups are not truly different; Bo Yi's clarity and Liu Xia Hui's harmony are ultimately one path. Do not deem the sober restraint of Mu Sheng a failing. I beg you send me a word showing your judgment.

    In this height of midsummer's heat, I pray for your continued good health. I send you a packet of poria for your alchemical work—let not sun and moon face each other alone in the furnace, and may the legendary arts of immortality mend this withering frame.
  footnotes:
    - 'Lushan and Tiger Creek: According to legend, the monk Yuan would walk his guests across this stream. When speaking with Tao Yuanming and Lu Xiujing, he became so absorbed in conversation that he unknowingly crossed the threshold—hence the name Tiger Creek.'
    - The reference to "Qu Yuan wakeful and Liu Ling drunk" invokes two famous figures representing opposite approaches to society—one who remained rigorous in principle, one who abandoned convention.
    - The final images of alchemy (sun and moon in the furnace) and the "legendary arts" (hongbao) are metaphorical wishes for the recipient's spiritual cultivation and preservation of health.
